<font color="#FF0000">CIVILIAN VIEWS OF VIETNAM VETS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Mar 15  8:01:18 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Don't you guys realize that Americans today respect, honor and sympathize with Vietnam Vets?<br><br>
Take for instance panhandlers who hold signs that say 'Vietnam Vet'.  If Vets were disliked, that would be a counter-productive panhandling technique.  These panhandlers, whether or not they are actually vets, understand the value of that title for eliciting sympathy.  And the public could not be sympathetic to Vietnam Vets if they did not respect them.<br><br>
Maybe its because of all the Vietnam War movies that have come out, like The Deer Hunter and Apocalypse Now.  At least for my generation, that is probably most people's primary source of knowledge about the war, or at least about its soldiers.  In such movies, the soldiers are always presented as ordinary, likeable, boys-next-door, who have been placed into a hellish situation and who really just wanted to go home. <br><br>
Tonight I read Howard Zinn's chapter on the Vietnam War, in his &quot;People's History of the United States&quot;.  He focuses on the protest movement, including the protest movement among the troops themselves: draft resistors, COs, AWOLs, &quot;fraggings&quot;, etc.  Did you know that near the end of the war almost 20% of the Vietnam troops were AWOL (177 per 1000)?  (and who blames 'em).<br><br>
I also read about the genocide against civilians, including the Massacre at My Lai.  I can see where that could elicit outrage against veterans.  Clearly that was a worst case scenario.  I have to believe most killing was against other armed combatants, not civilians, and when civilians were killed, it was more often 'colateral damage' from bombing etc. vs. systematic execution.  And when civilians were killed it was because an officer ordered them killed.  Even in Zinn's account of My Lai, a soldier performing the executions was crying and resisting the orders of his CO to execute the civilians.  I say blame the politicians first, officers second, enlisted (and conscripted) boys LAST.  These were just kids, fresh out of high-school, turned into trained killing machines by the US Armed Forces, given guns, dropped into battle, and ordered to kill or be killed.  The military consciously brainwashed soldiers to view the enemy ('gooks') as demons, enemies of democracy and all that is decent.  It was us or them.  It was the soldier's life or theirs.<br><br>
I also theorize that some American war protestors scapegoated Vets during the War not so much because they really blamed the Vets but as a demoralization technique.  Demoralization is a common technique in war, and if the protestors' war was the war to end the war, then demoralization of the troops would be one productive, if unethical strategy.  I am sure some protestors were demonizing vets to undermine their will to fight, and to discourage others from allowing themselves to be inducted, rather than because they held the vets responsible.  Once the demoralization of Vets was underway, others were probably misled into actually believing the soldiers were to blame, and once the tone was set, troops continued to be scapegoated even when the War was over.
